        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Hi @echasnovski \nAfter looking at the current implementation in _select.lua, I'd like to propose Option 1: a public vim.treesitter.select module with individual methods:\nvim.treesitter.select.parent(count)\nvim.treesitter.select.child(count)\nvim.treesitter.select.next(count)\nvim.treesitter.select.prev(count)\nReasoning:\nThis is consistent with how other vim.treesitter submodules are exposed (e.g., vim.treesitter.language, vim.treesitter.query).\nIndividual methods are more composable for custom mappings — users can directly reference them without constructing an opts table each time.\nThe internal _select.lua already has exactly this shape (select_parent, select_child, select_next, select_prev), so this is mostly a matter of making it public and renaming to drop the select_ prefix (since the module name already provides that context).\nA single vim.treesitter.select(opts) function would conflict with using select as both a callable and a module namespace.\nThis would let users write custom mappings like:\n-- LSP-first, tree-sitter fallback (the use case mentioned in the issue)\nvim.keymap.set('x', 'an', function()\n  local clients = vim.lsp.get_clients({ bufnr = 0, method = 'textDocument/selectionRange' })\n  if #clients > 0 then\n    vim.lsp.buf.selection_range(1)\n  else\n    vim.treesitter.select.parent(vim.v.count1)\n  end\nend)\nHappy to wait for the decision.\n",
